  "prompt": "What is the difference between clause and provision?",
  "response": "A clause and a provision are both components of a legal document or contract, but there are some key differences between them.\n\nA clause is a specific section or provision within a legal document or contract that deals with a particular topic or issue. It is a distinct part of the agreement, and may contain several provisions or sub-parts. For example, a contract might have a \"termination clause\" that specifies the conditions under which the contract can be ended.\n\nA provision, on the other hand, is a specific requirement or condition within a clause or legal document. Provisions are often more detailed and specific than clauses, and may outline the rights and obligations of the parties to the contract. For example, within the termination clause mentioned above, there might be a provision that states that either party can terminate the contract with 30 days' written notice.\n\nIn short, a clause is a section of a legal document that deals with a specific topic, while a provision is a specific requirement or condition within that clause or document.",
